That’s a compelling thought. It distinguishes identity from autobiography.

Here are a few variations that preserve the core idea:

You are more than your collection of memories. Step outside that box, and you’ll discover possibilities your past never recorded.

Or, more concise:

You are more than your memories. Step outside their walls and see what else you can become.

A more playful version:

You are more than your collection of memories. Climb out of that box every now and then—it turns out reality has a pretty big playground.

Or, in a more philosophical tone:

Memory explains where you’ve been. It doesn’t dictate where you can go. You are more than your collection of memories. Step outside that box, and have some fun.

It also pairs nicely with an idea you’ve explored before: memory is a useful map, but it isn’t the territory. Your past can inform your next step without completely defining it. Curiosity, imagination, and action let you create experiences that become tomorrow’s memories rather than simply replaying yesterday’s.